  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/134937446" />
    <a title="Marybeth" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1791369-marybeth"><img alt="Marybeth" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1241471753p2/1791369.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/134937446?book_show_action=true">Dec 13, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Marybeth" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Marybeth" href="/user/show/1791369-marybeth">Marybeth</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audio CD 9781419300448" href="/book/show/6659149-island-in-the-center-of-the-world">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer134937446" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6738289040912109654">While I do appreciate the amount of research that went into this book, the limitations of working with damaged &amp; incomplete records, the authors style was so over-the-top I just barely made it to the end. For every interesting detail there was a fanciful imagining about what else might have happened. It got so bad when I heard (I listened to the book on disc) &quot;let us imagine&quot; or &quot;we can suppose&quot; or some variation I would actually wince. It could have been 1/2 the length &amp; a better book.</span>
  <span id="freeText6738289040912109654" style="display:none">While I do appreciate the amount of research that went into this book, the limitations of working with damaged &amp; incomplete records, the authors style was so over-the-top I just barely made it to the end. For every interesting detail there was a fanciful imagining about what else might have happened. It got so bad when I heard (I listened to the book on disc) "let us imagine" or "we can suppose" or some variation I would actually wince. It could have been 1/2 the length &amp; a better book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6738289040912109654" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

